Indian Oil, Jet, Reliance Industries: India Stocks Preview

-- B y   S i d d h a r t h   P h i l i p   a n d   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 
2011-06-08T03:15:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-08/bharat-petroleum-reliance-communications-india-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the last close.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, rose
75.51 points, or 0.4 percent, to 18,495.62. The S&P CNX Nifty
Index on the National Stock Exchange advanced 0.4 percent to
5,556.15. The BSE 200 Index increased 0.5 percent to 2,298.40.
SGX S&P CNX Nifty Index futures for June delivery lost 0.8
percent to 5,520 as of 10:59 a.m. in  Singapore .  Entertainment Network India Ltd. (ENIL)  : The company
controlled by billionaire Indu Jain may purchase rival  radio
stations  should the government allow mergers in its new policy
this year, Chief Executive Officer Prashant Panday said. The
shares climbed 0.4 percent to 244.35 rupees.  Indian Oil Corp. (IOCL IN): The country’s biggest refiner
issued its first spot tender for crude for loading in August,
official documents obtained by Bloomberg News show. The company
bought seven cargoes totaling about 6.6 million barrels of West
African grades for loading in July.  Separately, the company has begun discussions with overseas
companies to jointly develop a 4.5 billion rupee liquefied
natural gas terminal at Ennore in the south of India, Business
Standard reported today, citing Chairman R.S. Butola.  Petronet
LNG Ltd. (PLNG)   may join as a local partner, the paper said.
Indian Oil fell 0.2 percent to 319.15 rupees. Petronet increased
0.1 percent to 139 rupees.  Jet Airways India Ltd. (JETIN)  : The biggest airline was
lowered to “neutral” from “overweight” by Mark Carmeron Ross Webb, an analyst at HSBC Holdings Plc. with a price estimate of
500 rupees per share. The shares increased 2.3 percent to 459.05
rupees.  Oil & Natural Gas Corp. (ONGC IN): ONGC Videsh Ltd., a unit
of India’s largest state-owned oil explorer, and  GAIL India Ltd. (GAIL) 
 plan to jointly buy an 8.4 percent stake from Exxon
Mobil Corp. in  Kazakhstan ’s Kashagan oil field, valued at $5
billion, the Hindustan Times reported. The state-run companies
have submitted a non-binding bid to Exxon Mobil and need the
Indian cabinet’s approval for the investment, according to the
report, which cited an unidentified official familiar with the
matter. Oil & Natural Gas added 0.2 percent to 276.35 rupees.
GAIL advanced 0.8 percent to 435.75 rupees.  Reliance Communications Ltd. (RCOM)  :  Carlyle Group  and
TPG Capital are among companies in talks to buy a stake in
Reliance’s mobile-phone towers unit, three people with knowledge
of the matter said. The shares declined 0.5 percent to 92.05
rupees.  Reliance Industries Ltd. (RIL)  : India’s most valuable
company and its Canadian partner Niko Resources Ltd. have told
India’s oil ministry that they are unable to raise gas output
from one of their blocks until 2014, Mint reported, citing
minutes of a May 2 meeting. Reliance surged 2.2 percent to
958.25 rupees.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Siddharth Philip in Mumbai at 
 sphilip3@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 